  "prompt": "What is the best WYSIWYG editor for Drupal 7?",
  "response": "Choosing the best WYSIWYG (What You See Is What You Get) editor for Drupal 7 often depends on your specific needs and preferences, but a few options have consistently been popular and well-regarded within the Drupal community:\n\n1. **CKEditor**: This is one of the most popular WYSIWYG editors for Drupal 7. It is highly configurable, has a wide range of plugins, and offers a user-friendly interface. CKEditor is known for its stability and robust set of features, which include image uploading, media embedding, and spell checking.\n\n2. **TinyMCE**: Another widely-used WYSIWYG editor, TinyMCE is lightweight and highly customizable. It comes with a variety of plugins and is easy to integrate with Drupal 7. TinyMCE is also known for its good balance between functionality and performance.\n\n3. **ALOHA Editor**: Aloha is known for its true \"inline editing\" capability, which offers a different experience compared to more traditional WYSIWYG editors. It's designed to be flexible and modular, allowing you to pick and choose which features you want to incorporate.\n\n4. **WYSIWYG Module**: While not an editor itself, the WYSIWYG module allows you to integrate a variety of WYSIWYG editors into your Drupal site. It acts as a bridge between Drupal and editors like CKEditor and TinyMCE, enabling you to quickly switch between them or try out different options with minimal effort.\n\n5. **IMCE**: This is an image/file uploader and browser that often complements WYSIWYG editors like CKEditor and TinyMCE. While it does not offer text editing capabilities, it provides an easy way to handle media, which is a crucial aspect of many content editing workflows.\n\nWhen choosing an editor, also consider factors such as ease of use, the specific needs of your content creators, compatibility with other modules, and ongoing community support. You may also want to check recent reviews or community forums for the latest recommendations, as the landscape can change with updates and the emergence of new tools or versions.",
